It happens. Debbie was very nice and made sure I was taken care of. Thank You!  I ordered a pizza from Pete’s through a web order. Requested to have it made well done. My pizza was not well done at all, crust was nowhere near done not to mention well done. I called, I spoke to someone and was assured I will have a credit placed under my phone number. Was told to make sure I call to be able to use the credit. Well here I am, I called Pete’s today to finally use my credit. At first the credit wasn’t found, then I guess it was — have no clue. UPDATE: Management reached out and said they would refund the order.  We ordered pizza from Pete's at 7:10 tonight. At 8:30, we received our pizza. Our two liter of pop was literally INSIDE the pizza box. When our driver delivered it, he actually had to open the pizza box to physically remove the two liter from the pizza box and didn't even apologize. When we opened the pizza box ourselves, the pizza was all pushed to one side of the box.  We contacted GrubHub, sent them a photo, and the only thing the restaurant was willing to do was pick up the pizza and give us a refund. It is pretty annoying to wait 80 minutes for a pizza delivery and then have no pizza.  If that wasn't bad enough, at 10:20, they still hadn't picked up the pizza, so, we contacted GrubHub and let them know we couldn't wait any longer for the driver to come back and pick up the pizza. GrubHub contacted the store again, and they refused to refund the pizza. They said the only thing they were willing to do was to remake the pizza.  1) Why in the world would be want a replacement pizza when we wouldn't receive it until over FOUR hours after we ordered our pizza. 2) If we couldn't wait any longer for the driver to pick up the messed up pizza, how would we be able to wait another hour for a replacement pizza?  So in the end, we got this jacked up pizza that a two liter rolled into at full cost. Completely ridiculous customer service. Avoid Pete's Pizza.

Family ordered two pizzas to dine in. One was delivered to the table and we waited for the other. And waited. And waited. Server said it would be a few minutes. And we waited. Server came back and said the pizza would be right out. And we waited.  Server came back again and informed us that the pizza had been given to a delivery driver by mistake and they would have to cook another. And we waited. Server came back and said it would be another 10 minutes. Then she corrected herself and said it would be 12 minutes. Then a manager shuffled over and mumbled something about 5 minutes and asked if I wanted a beer. I was already on my second soda so I declined. And so we waited.  Finally after 30 minutes of waiting, the pizza was delivered. It was fine. Nothing special. If that’s the “best pizza in Chicago” like people claim, then I’m about to be sorely disappointed in my previously held expectations for Chicago pizza. Manager wandered back out after we finished eating and mumbled something else about a discount. Couldn’t quite catch it. He again asked if I wanted a beer. By that time I was just ready to leave. We got the bill and they had taken something like 25% off one of the pizzas. Whoopee. We still tipped the server 20% because it wasn’t her fault. But you’d think that a pizza place that has been business almost 70 YEARS might, you know, have some kind of system in place where they don’t give dine-in pizzas to delivery drivers. Seems reeeeeeeal basic to me. Like, the worst pizza places I’ve ever eaten at still managed to figure out how to take the pizza from the kitchen to my table. But I’m no pizza expert...  As far as atmosphere goes, during our interminable wait, we were able to enjoy Pete’s current avant-garde decor approach of paint literally peeling from the walls. Gave it a real rustic vibe...  This was our first time at Pete’s. See if you can guess if there will be a second time.
